    "narrative": "The lineup for Ghost Ride the WHIP today leans heavily into platoon advantages and park factors, with **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) and **Seiya Suzuki** (73.90) leading the charge. **Mickey Moniak** benefits from a massive 14% boost due to his dynamic platoon profile against a non-prime version of Spencer Strider, while **Seiya Suzuki** is primed for a big day thanks to a favorable wind forecast and a slow-delivering opposing pitcher that bolsters his stolen base potential\u2014a crucial element for our efficiency strategy. **Brice Turang** (73.40) also earns a high-tier start, as his 17% SP skill boost and favorable batting order position maximize his chances to produce against Zack Littell.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was leaving **Gabriel Moreno** (54.31) out of the rotation. While he holds a strong score, his projection suffered slightly from the platoon disadvantage against Matthew Boyd and the optimizer\u2019s prioritization of **Vinnie Pasquantino** (67.69), whose higher ceiling against Luis Castillo\u2014boosted by a 14% platoon advantage\u2014made him the statistically superior option. We are also monitoring **Corbin Carroll** (64.33) closely; while he remains a must-start for his speed, his score is slightly suppressed by a 4% penalty for facing an elite hold pitcher, though the favorable wind conditions help mitigate that risk. \n\nWe must remain vigilant regarding the \"Lineup Pending\" designations for players like **Dalton Rushing** and **Luis Campusano**. Their current scores reflect assumed order slots, and any drop in the batting order could immediately shift them into the marginal category. Furthermore, **Tyler Soderstrom** faces a tough test against Parker Messick, with his score hampered by a negative 16% SP skill adjustment. As always, these bench players\u2014including **Kyle Karros** and **Alex Freeland**\u2014stand ready to rotate in if late-breaking lineup news suggests a shift in opportunity.",
